Feature: Conversation watching and indexing
  Scenario: Non-JSONL files are ignored
    Given the Machinen daemon is running
    When a non-.jsonl file is created or modified under ~/.claude/projects/
    Then no spec update is triggered

  Scenario: Rapid JSONL writes are coalesced into a single spec update
    Given the Machinen daemon is running
    When a .jsonl file receives multiple writes in quick succession
    Then a single spec update is triggered after the writes stabilise

Feature: Spec file creation
  Scenario: First spec for a branch with conversation data
    Given a branch has no existing spec file
    And conversation data is available for that branch
    When the daemon processes messages for that branch
    Then a spec file is created at ~/.machinen/specs/<repo_slug>/<branch>.md
    And the spec file contains behaviours extracted from the conversation data

  Scenario: No spec file is created when no conversation data exists
    Given a branch has no existing spec file
    And no conversation data is available for that branch
    When the daemon checks for updates on that branch
    Then no spec file is created

  Scenario: Repo slug is derived from the repository path
    Given a repository at an absolute path such as /Users/justin/rw/repo
    When a spec is created for a branch in that repository
    Then the repo slug directory is formed by replacing path separators with hyphens and stripping the leading separator
    And the spec file appears under ~/.machinen/specs/Users-justin-rw-repo/

Feature: Spec file content and format
  Scenario: Spec output is Gherkin
    Given conversation excerpts are available for a branch
    When the spec file is generated
    Then the file contains Feature blocks with Scenario entries using Given/When/Then steps
    And the file does not contain preamble or commentary outside the Gherkin structure

  Scenario: Spec contains only externally observable behaviours
    Given conversation excerpts reference both internal implementation details and externally observable behaviours
    When the spec file is generated
    Then the spec includes only behaviours verifiable through the product's external interfaces
    And the spec does not include scenarios about internal function calls, database schemas, environment variables, or subprocess flags

  Scenario: System tags in conversations are excluded from the spec
    Given conversation messages contain system-reminder, IDE opened-file, or IDE selection tags
    When the daemon extracts text from those messages
    Then the tag content does not appear in the generated spec

Feature: Spec file updates
  Scenario: Spec is updated when new conversation data arrives
    Given a branch already has a spec file
    And new conversation messages have been recorded for that branch
    When the daemon processes the new messages
    Then the spec file at ~/.machinen/specs/<repo_slug>/<branch>.md is updated
    And the updated spec reflects the new conversation content

  Scenario: Spec updates preserve previously captured behaviours
    Given a branch already has a spec file from a previous update
    When additional conversation messages arrive for that branch
    Then the spec is revised in light of the new information
    And previously captured behaviours that are still valid are preserved

Feature: Reset command
  Scenario: Running --reset regenerates the spec from scratch
    Given a branch already has a spec file and conversations have been partially processed
    When the user runs the daemon with --reset <branch>
    Then the existing spec file is deleted
    And a new spec is generated from all available conversation data for that branch

  Scenario: Running --reset with no branch name shows usage
    Given the user runs the daemon with --reset but no branch argument
    Then an error message is displayed showing the expected usage
    And the process exits with a non-zero status

  Scenario: Running --reset for a branch with no conversations reports no data
    Given no conversations have been recorded for a branch
    When the user runs --reset for that branch
    Then a message is displayed indicating no conversations were found

Feature: Daemon startup
  Scenario: Daemon is started via npm start
    Given the user is in the machinen package directory
    When the user runs npm start
    Then the daemon begins watching ~/.claude/projects/ for JSONL file changes

Feature: Source of truth and data integrity
  Scenario: Multiple conversations can be associated with a single branch
    Given two or more Claude Code conversations are conducted on the same branch
    When the daemon indexes those conversations
    Then spec updates for that branch draw from all associated conversations